<br>
A level cap of 60 and AA skills as an alternative for all players.<br>
<br>
Consider a team with one cleric, one chanter, one warrior, one monk, one rogue and a wizard (yea, let's toss in a wizard, why not?). All of them 60, no AA, Luclin just came out. They start xp-ing in a zone that gives good experience for their level. <br>
<br>
After a while, the rogue gets this cool AA skill that gives him the opportunity to assassinate every 40th mob. Suddenly, killing the same amount of critters goes 2.5 percent faster, so the monk can pull more, OR the uptime goes down with 2.5 percent if there are no more mobs available. <br>
<br>
Then, the wizard gets SCFM3, so the amount of damage the wizzy does increases with 14 percent or so. Again, the average damage done by the team goes up with, say, 14 percent divided by 6 (I know, a VERY rough estimate) and again, the same amount of mobs will be killed 2 to 3 percent faster. Etc., Etc, Etc. <br>
<br>
In the end this team will be able to kill the same amount of mobs 20 percent or so faster, and will meet the limitations of the zone they're fighting in: No more mobs up, so less uptime so more time to med for the wizzy. This effect of AA points will mean that a satisfactory xp area gives comparably better damage output for the wizard.<br>
<br>
By now, a few things could happen:<br>
A. Group is not too ambitious, and prefers to stay in that zone. The more AA points this team gathers, the more efficient the wizzy gets. This will probably bore the entire team almost to death, so...<br>
B. Group moves to another zone, with more challenging mobs. Eventually, if Verant continues this system of AA exp and not raises the level cap beyond 60, this will mean that our Example Team will move from dark blue mobs to even conning mobs, and after that to yellow and even red mobs (ToV ae team? Anyone?). <br>
<br>
Still, the big difference will be, that the need to move on to a heavier zone will be because people want to move on, not because their mobs are all of a sudden light blue or green to them. And the slower the team moves, the better the wizard looks, not because of our own AA skills, but also because of other's.<br>
<br>
